<paragraph id="2DEA8F9A536338362CCB8944E25C3959" pageId="36" pageNumber="61">
<taxonomicName id="B317E989B96CC9DCED5F288B7D62FCBD" authorityName="Bunwong, Chantar. &amp; S. C. Keeley" authorityYear="2014" baseAuthorityName="Bunwong, Chantar. &amp; S. C. Keeley" baseAuthorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Cyanthillium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="36" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="montanum">
<emphasis id="E87C5C9524F75B8E773271D2DAD7ED79" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="61">Cyanthillium montanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is separated from 
<taxonomicName id="460B10583B852BB395F8F5149A28EB92" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Cyanthillium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="36" pageNumber="61" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cinereum">
<emphasis id="4659ED7684F27DDDE10D3E43A408A15A" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="61">Cyanthillium cinereum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having villose to tomentose hairs on stems, branches, lower leaf surfaces and involucres, rather than appressed sericeous hairs. This species restricted to pine oak forest on the mountains.
</paragraph>
